The board may refuse to issue a certificate, or may suspend, revoke, impose probationary conditions upon, impose an administrative fine, issue a written reprimand or admonishment, or any combination thereof regarding any certificate holder upon proof that the certificate holder has:
Committed any crime, act of dishonesty, or corruption. If the act constitutes a crime, conviction in a criminal proceeding is not a condition precedent to disciplinary action. Upon conviction of the crime, the judgment and sentence are presumptive evidence at the ensuing disciplinary hearing of the guilt of the certificate holder or applicant. Conviction includes all instances in which a plea of no contest is the basis of conviction;
Misrepresented or concealed a material fact in obtaining, renewing or reinstating a certificate;
Committed any unfair, false, misleading, or deceptive act or practice;
Been incompetent or negligent in the practice of respiratory care;
Violated any state statute or administrative regulation governing the practice of respiratory care or any activities undertaken by a respiratory care practitioner;
Failed to comply with an order issued by the board or an assurance of voluntary compliance;
Violated the code of ethics as set forth in administrative regulations promulgated by the board; or
Violated any applicable provision of any federal or state law.
